Marina Oswald gave as her opinion that the mail-order coupon was in Oswald's handwriting.
When shown the revolver, she stated that she recognized it as the one owned by her husband.
in the picture she took in late March or early April 1963 when the family was living on Neely Street in Dallas.
Police found an empty revolver holster when they searched Oswald's room on Beckley Avenue after his arrest.
Marina Oswald testified that this was the holster which contained the revolver in the photographs taken on Neely Street.
Approximately 15 minutes before the shooting of Tippit, Oswald was seen leaving his roominghouse.
He was wearing a zipper jacket which he had not been wearing moments before when he had arrived home.
When Oswald was arrested, he did not have a jacket.
Shortly after Tippit was slain, policemen found a light-colored zipper jacket along the route taken by the killer as he attempted to escape.
According to Patrolman Poe this description came from Mrs. Markham and Mrs. Barbara Jeanette Davis.
or eight inches, about 145 pounds, end quote, and wearing a white jacket.
two witnesses, Warren Reynolds and B. M. Patterson, saw the gunman run toward the rear of a gasoline service station on Jefferson Boulevard.
