wasn't the day before. Perhaps 3 days before, end quote.
Marina Oswald speculated that the incident may have been unrelated to an actual threat.
She said, quote, It might have been that he was just trying to test me.
not really as a joke but rather to simply wound me, to make me feel bad, end quote.
was of no probative value in the Commission's decision concerning the identity of the assassin of President Kennedy.
possessed the capability to hit his target with two out of three shots under the conditions described in chapter 3.
(3) his experience and practice after leaving the Marine Corps, and (4) the accuracy of the weapon and the quality of the ammunition.
with the alinement of the assassin's rifle, at a range of 177 to 266 feet.
so that the President would have been moving in an almost straight line away from the assassin's rifle.
which is ordinarily required when a marksman must raise his rifle as a target moves farther away.
Four marksmanship experts testified before the Commission.
testified that the shots which struck the President in the neck and in the head were, quote, not particularly difficult, end quote.
once you know that you must put the crosshairs on the target and that is all that is necessary.
Well, in order to achieve three hits, it would not be required that a man be an exceptional shot. A proficient man with this weapon, yes, end quote.
of the Marine Corps School at Quantico, Virginia.
it just takes a minor move in aiming to bring the crosshairs to bear, and then it is a quick squeeze.
I consider it a real advantage, particularly at the range of 100 yards, in identifying your target.
It allows you to see your target clearly, and it is still of a minimum amount of power that it doesn't exaggerate your own body movements.
in relation to the target as opposed to iron sights with aligning the sights and then aligning them on the target, end quote.
at a distance of 265.3 feet was, quote, an easy shot, end quote.
made an almost stationary target while he was aiming in, very little movement if any, end quote.
In accordance with standard Marine procedures, Oswald received extensive training in marksmanship.
During the first week of an intensive 8-week training period he received instruction in sighting, aiming, and manipulation of the trigger.
He went through a series of exercises called dry firing where he assumed all positions which would later be used in the qualification course.
firing 50 rounds each day for five days.
which was 2 points above the minimum for qualifications as a "sharpshooter" in a scale of marksman, sharpshooter, expert.
.45 caliber pistol, and 12-gauge riot gun.
Based on the general Marine Corps ratings, Lt. Col. A. G. Folsom, Jr.
as a, quote, rather poor shot, end quote.
he had just completed a very intensive preliminary training period.
He had the services of an experienced highly trained coach.
He had high motivation. He had presumably a good to excellent rifle and good ammunition.
and he probably didn't have as high a motivation because he was no longer in recruit training and under the care of the drill instructor.
because he may well have carried this rifle for quite some time, and it got banged around in normal usage.
that Oswald was a good shot, somewhat better than or equal to -- better than the average let us say.
As compared to a civilian who had not received this intensive training, he would be considered as a good to excellent shot. End quote.
firing it, with 10 rounds.
and as compared to the average male of his age throughout the civilian, throughout the United States, that he is an excellent shot, end quote.
using a .22 caliber bolt-action rifle belonging either to Robert or Robert's in-laws.
After he left the Marines and before departing for Russia, Oswald, his brother, and a third companion went hunting for squirrels and rabbits.
Lee Oswald exhibited an average amount of proficiency with that weapon.
Oswald obtained a hunting license, joined a hunting club and went hunting about six times, as discussed more fully in chapter 6.
he again went hunting with his brother, Robert, and used a borrowed .22 caliber bolt-action rifle.
After Oswald purchased the Mannlicher-Carcano rifle, he told his wife that he practiced with it.
Marina Oswald testified that on one occasion she saw him take the rifle, concealed in a raincoat, from the house on Neely Street.
Oswald told her he was going to practice with it.
According to George De Mohrenschildt, Oswald said that he went target shooting with that rifle.
sighting with the telescopic lens and operating the bolt.
which would indicate that Oswald practiced operating the bolt.
to 7.9 seconds.
were capable of firing the shots which were fired by the assassin on November 22, 1963.
The ammunition used by the assassin was manufactured by Western Cartridge Co. of East Alton, Illinois.
and the Infantry Weapons Evaluation Branch of the U.S. Army. There were no misfires.
from a tower at three silhouette targets at distances of 175, 240, and 265 feet.
