Oswald had expressed approval of President Kennedy's active role in the area of civil rights.
and had lost his desire to do so because of the bureaucracy and red tape which he had encountered.
His unhappy experience with the Cuban consul seems thus to have reduced his enthusiasm for the Castro regime and his desire to go to Cuba.
after he had assassinated the American President, it does not appear that he had any plans to go there.
$170 in a wallet in his wife's room in Irving.
with $13.87 when considerably greater resources were available to him.
and raises serious questions as to whether or not he ever expected to escape.
