Chapter 7. Lee Harvey Oswald: Background and Possible Motives, Part 6.
and which received publicity there prior to the assassination.
and in the extreme anti-Kennedy newspaper advertisement and handbills that appeared in Dallas at the time of the President's visit there.
or rightwing extremism which may have existed in the city of Dallas had any connection with Oswald's actions on November 22, 1963.
There is, of course, no way to judge what the effect of the general political ferment present in that city might have been, even though Oswald was aware of it.
On October 23rd, I had attended a ultra-right meeting headed by General Edwin A. Walker, who lives in Dallas.
As you can see, political friction between "left" and "right" is very great here.
Could you advise me as to the general view we have on the American Civil Liberties Union? End quote.
even though he did, as he told Johnson, attend a meeting at which General Walker spoke to approximately 1,300 persons.
to shoot General Walker.
The relations between Lee and Marina Oswald are of great importance in any attempt to understand Oswald's possible motivation.
he and his wife spent every weekend but one together at the Irving, Texas home of Mrs. Ruth Paine, who was then separated from her husband.
when his wife asked Oswald not to come to Irving.
During the week, Oswald lived in a roominghouse in Dallas, but he usually called his wife on the telephone twice a day.
She testified that after his return from Mexico Oswald, quote, changed for the better.
He began to treat me better. He helped me more -- although he always did help. But he was more attentive, end quote.
Marina Oswald attributed that to their living apart and to the imminent birth of their second child.
She testified that Oswald, quote, was very happy, end quote, about the birth of the child.
might also have been important to him. It would not have been the first time that Oswald sought closer ties with his family in time of adversity.
His past relationships with his wife had been stormy, however, and it did not seem that she respected him very much.
They had been married after a courtship of only about 6 weeks, a part of which Oswald spent in the hospital.
Oswald's diary reports that he married his wife shortly after his proposal of marriage to another girl had been rejected.
In spite of fact I married Marina to hurt Ella (the girl that had rejected him) I found myself in love with Marina, end quote.
that she would be able to leave the Soviet Union. Marina Oswald has denied this.
Marina Oswald expressed one aspect of her husband's attitude toward her when she testified that, quote, Lee wanted me to go to Russia.
if he wanted me to go then that meant that he didn't love me, and that in that case what was the idea of coming to the United States in the first place.
Lee would say that it would be better for me if I went to Russia. I did not know why. I did not know what he had in mind.
He said he loved me but that it would be better for me if I went to Russia, and what he had in mind I don't know. End quote.
Many times Oswald has recalled this matter to me and said that I am just waiting for an opportunity to hurt him.
It has been the cause of many of our arguments. End quote. Oswald claimed that his wife preferred others to him.
and also about Mrs. Paine.
1963.
The instability of their relations was probably a function of the personalities of both people. Oswald was overbearing in relations with his wife.
He apparently attempted to be "the Commander" by dictating many of the details of their married life.
he made no attempt to help her and there are other indications that he did not want her to learn that language.
that Oswald stated that he did not speak English in his family because he did not want them to become Americanized.
Marina Oswald's inability to speak English also made it more difficult for her to have an independent existence in this country.
did not want her to drink, smoke or wear cosmetics and generally treated her with lack of respect in the presence of others.
The difficulties which Oswald's problems would have caused him in any relationship were probably not reduced by his wife's conduct.
thought that Marina Oswald was immature in her thinking and partly responsible for the difficulties that the Oswalds were having at that time.
Mrs. Ford said that Marina Oswald admitted that she provoked Oswald on occasion.
There can be little doubt that some provocation existed.
Oswald once struck his wife because of a letter which she wrote to a former boyfriend in Russia.
In the letter Marina Oswald stated that her husband had changed a great deal and that she was very lonely in the United States.
She was, quote, sorry that I had not married him (the Russian boyfriend) instead, that it would have been much easier for me, end quote.
because of insufficient postage, which apparently resulted from an increase in postal rates of which his wife had been unaware.
Oswald read the letter, but refused to believe that it was sincere, even though his wife insisted to him that it was.
Generally, I think that was right, for such things that is the right thing to do. There was some grounds for it. End quote.
it appears that Marina Oswald also complained that her husband was not able to provide more material things for her.
The De Mohrenschildts also testified that, quote, right in front, end quote, of Oswald Marina Oswald complained about Oswald's inadequacy as a husband.
and that Oswald, quote, was not a man, end quote. She also told Mrs. Paine that she was not satisfied with her sexual relations with Oswald.
Marina Oswald also ridiculed her husband's political views, thereby tearing down his view of his own importance.
He was very much interested in autobiographical works of outstanding statesmen of the United States, to whom his wife thought he compared himself.
as to the fact that he was an outstanding man, end quote.
She said that she, quote, always tried to point out to him that he was a man like any others who were around us. But he simply could not understand that? End quote.
Jeanne De Mohrenschildt, however, thought that Marina Oswald, quote, said things that will hurt men's pride, end quote.
She said that if she ever spoke to her husband the way Marina Oswald spoke to her husband, quote, we would not last long, end quote.
Nobody said anything good about him. End quote.
She had, quote, the impression that he was just pushed, pushed, pushed, and she Marina Oswald was probably nagging, nagging, nagging, end quote.
She thought that he might not have become involved in the assassination if people had been kinder to him.
things apparently went quite smoothly from the time Oswald returned from Mexico until the weekend of November 16 to 17, 1963.
Mrs. Paine was planning a birthday party for one of her children on that weekend and her husband, Michael, was to be at the house.
Marina Oswald said that she knew her husband did not like Michael Paine and so she asked him not to come out that weekend, even though he wanted to do so.
that he shouldn't come every week, that perhaps it is not convenient for Ruth that the whole family be there, live there, end quote.
She testified that he responded, quote, As you wish. If you don't want me to come, I won't, end quote.
Ruth Paine testified that she heard Marina Oswald tell Oswald about the birthday party.
Ruth Paine and Marina Oswald decided to call Oswald at the place where he was living, unbeknownst to them, under the name of O. H. Lee.
They asked for Lee Oswald who was not called to the telephone because he was known by the other name.
he did not want his landlady to know his real name because she might read in the paper of the fact that he had been in Russia and that he had been questioned, end quote.
and he thought that he loses jobs because the FBI visits the place of his employment, end quote.
which had led to the disclosure of his defection in New Orleans.
it does not appear that he ever lost his job because of its activities, although he may well not have been aware of that fact.
to some extent after his Fair Play for Cuba Committee activities had become known, he exaggerated their concern for him.
Marina Oswald thought he did so in order to emphasize his importance.
to the Soviet Embassy in Washington, he asked about the entrance visas for which he and his wife had previously applied.
warned me that if I engaged in F.P.C.C. activities in Texas the F.B.I. will again take an interest in me, end quote.
to the time of the assassination.
The claimed warning was one more of Oswald's fabrications.
